{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619985"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16598"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.35,0,0.04,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68706"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9289"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54163"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5219"},{"type":"tags","id":"10025"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22891"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68706"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner requesting information about paracetamol safety. She takes regular paracetamol for chronic headaches and wants to understand how the medication is processed by her body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary metabolic pathway of paracetamol at therapeutic doses?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxidation to NAPQI","Glucuronidation and sulfation","Conjugation with glycine","Direct renal excretion unchanged","Reduction to inactive metabolites"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary metabolic pathway for paracetamol involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eglucuronidation and sulfation \u003C/strong\u003Ein the liver. Approximately 80-90% of a therapeutic dose undergoes this conjugation process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidation to NAPQI\u003C/strong\u003E occurs for only about 5-10% of paracetamol through cytochrome P450 metabolism. This toxic metabolite is normally detoxified by conjugation with glutathione.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect renal excretion unchanged\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for only a small percentage (2-5%) of paracetamol elimination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjugation with glycine\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant metabolic pathway for paracetamol metabolism, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction to inactive metabolites\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant route of paracetamol metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding paracetamol metabolism is clinically important because in overdose, the glucuronidation and sulfation pathways become saturated, leading to increased NAPQI formation and potential hepatotoxicity when glutathione stores are depleted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paracetamol is metabolised primarily by conjugation with glucuronide and sulfate in the liver.","A small portion of paracetamol is metabolised by cytochrome P450 to form the toxic metabolite N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine (NAPQI).","At therapeutic doses, NAPQI is detoxified by conjugation with glutathione."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54163"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54163"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T12:17:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T12:17:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9289"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68706"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdA